percent-overall-progression-leverage-ratios.jpg\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/02111029/transition-spire-23-percent-overall-progression-leverage-ratios.jpg 1200w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/02111029/transition-spire-23-percent-overall-progression-leverage-ratios-297x198.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/02111029/transition-spire-23-percent-overall-progression-leverage-ratios-800x533.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/02111029/transition-spire-23-percent-overall-progression-leverage-ratios-120x80.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/02111029/transition-spire-23-percent-overall-progression-leverage-ratios-768x512.jpg 768w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/02111029/transition-spire-23-percent-overall-progression-leverage-ratios-696x464.jpg 696w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/02111029/transition-spire-23-percent-overall-progression-leverage-ratios-1068x712.jpg 1068w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/02111029/transition-spire-23-percent-overall-progression-leverage-ratios-630x420.jpg 630w\"></a></p><p><span data-ez-name=\"bikerumor_com-box-4\"></span>The Transition Spire varies in chainstay length dependent on frame size. The small, medium and large frames rock a 446mm chainstay while the stays of the larger frames are longer at 452mm.</p><figure id=\"attachment_260749\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-260749\"><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/02101833/transition-spire-leverage-ration-graph-long-short-c